library(tmap)

Warning: package tmap was built under R version 4.4.1

Lets read a raster image

myras <- terra::rast("../data/ts_2016.1007_1013.L4.LCHMP3.CIcyano.MAXIMUM_7day.tif")

plot it

plot(myras)

Basic properties

ncol(myras) * nrow(myras) == ncell(myras)

[1] TRUE

QUESTION: whats the data structure of a raster file?

Get values by index

myras[1]


myras[33961]
NA

Or by row, column


#[row, column]  

myras[132, 164]

Two questions:

  1. How is single indexing different than row, column indexing?
  2. For row, column indexing, what other information is useful/required to know what youre doing?

Frequency of values


terra::freq(myras)
NA
NA

Whats the output???

Lets use it to make a quick histogram

terra::freq(myras) %>%  
  ggplot(., aes(x = value, y = count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Was the plot useful? Why or why not?

Lets try again

terra::freq(myras) %>%
  dplyr::filter(value < 252) %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x = value, y = count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Better?

Raster aggregation

Why might we want to change the resolution of a raster?

Lets break down the code

terra::aggregate(myras, 2, fun = max)
class       : SpatRaster 
dimensions  : 373, 129, 1  (nrow, ncol, nlyr)
resolution  : 600, 600  (x, y)
extent      : 598816.2, 676216.2, 4804394, 5028194  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
coord. ref. : WGS 84 / UTM zone 18N (EPSG:32618) 
source(s)   : memory
name        : ts_2016.1007_1013.L4.LCHMP3.CIcyano.MAXIMUM_7day 
min value   :                                              120 
max value   :                                              252

What happened?

More obvious comparisons

terra::aggregate(myras, 2, fun = max) %>% plot()

terra::aggregate(myras, 5, fun = max) %>% plot()

Interpret the results. How do they differ in spatial scale, generalization, etc.?

Different functions lead to different results

raster::aggregate(myras, 5, fun = max) %>% plot()

raster::aggregate(myras, 5, fun = mean) %>% plot()

Again, how do they differ?

We can also polygonize (if wed like)

poly1 <- terra::as.polygons(myras, dissolve = T)

tmap_mode("view")
 tmap mode set to "view".
tm_shape(poly1) + tm_polygons()

Zoom in. What do you see? What was the result?

Might be more obvious if we aggregate first

myras %>% 
  terra::aggregate(., 4, fun = max) %>%
  terra::as.polygons(., dissolve = T) %>%
  tm_shape(.) + 
  tm_polygons()
